    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Hey,</p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Day 35. By now you may be ordering equipment or working through the install. Today's point is simple: some tasks are not worth DIY-ing even if you are capable.</p>
    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:28px 0 10px 0;">1. The 240V electrical circuit</h2>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Most HVAC equipment needs a dedicated 240V circuit, correct breaker, wire gauge, outdoor disconnect, and whip. Local rules vary, but new high-amp circuits are often the part to hire out because the downside of a mistake is severe.</p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 22px 0;"><a href="{{ cta_url }}" style="color:#FF6B2B;font-weight:600;text-decoration:underline;">Get matched with a licensed electrician for your HVAC circuit</a></p>
    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:28px 0 10px 0;">2. Refrigerant work on non-pre-charged systems</h2>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Pressure testing, evacuation, and charging require certification, tools, and precision. If your project is not pre-charged, price a partial-scope HVAC visit before buying tools you may use once.</p>
    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:28px 0 10px 0;">3. Final commissioning</h2>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">Commissioning is post-install verification: airflow, temperature split, refrigerant behavior, controls, and written notes. It is especially useful for multi-zone systems and heat pumps.</p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Day 45 is the last email: the paperwork to keep for credits, rebates, warranty, and tax season.</p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:20px 0 4px 0;">&mdash; NailTheQuote</p>
